Unlearn & Relearn Series, Part 4: V8 optimizes your code. Then it throws that optimization away. Here’s why.
The Mystery That Haunted Me
I had a function that processed user data. It ran fast, really fast, thousands of times per second.
Then one day, it slowed down. Same code. Same shape of data, or so I thought. Nothing in the profiler pointed at anything obviously wrong. No new loops, no new network calls, no bloated dependency. Just slower.
I asked the AI. It said: “Use a more efficient algorithm.” Not helpful, the algorithm hadn’t changed.
So I went digging. I read V8’s own documentation. I found the thing that explained everything.
V8 optimizes your code based on the shape of your data, an object’s properties, and the order they were assigned in. Keep calling a function with objects of a consistent shape, and V8 compiles it down into fast, specialized machine code. Change that shape, even slightly, and V8 can’t trust that machine code anymore, it throws it away and falls back to slower, generic bytecode.
That’s called deoptimization. And it’s why code that looks completely unchanged can quietly run at a different speed.
The Thought Experiment
Imagine a factory assembly line built to build blue cars. Every car that comes through is blue. The workers know exactly what to do. Everything moves fast.
Then a red car arrives. The automated systems don’t know what to do with it. They have to shut the line down, reconfigure, and rebuild.
That’s deoptimization. V8 builds an optimized “assembly line” for your function based on the shapes it’s seen. The moment a different shape shows up, it has to tear that line down and start over.
